<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="487" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[113,647,828,905]" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">
DISTRIBUTION. — Currently, the genus is only known from the islands of Aneityum, Espiritu Santo, Maewo, and Malekula, 
<collectingCountry box="[259,345,881,905]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="487" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[111,648,928,1138]" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">
DIAGNOSIS. — 
<taxonomicName authority="Ober &amp; Staniczek, 2009" authorityName="Ober &amp; Staniczek" authorityYear="2009" box="[260,383,928,952]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Vanuatubasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[260,383,928,952]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Vanuatubasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[388,453,928,952]" pageId="2" pageNumber="487" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1891" box="[554,640,928,952]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Nesobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="2" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[554,640,928,952]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Nesobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from the latter in the following characters: 1) superior anal appendages of males broad and short (
<figureCitation box="[122,180,1008,1032]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[113,124,1485,1502]" captionTargetBox="[113,1209,215,1445]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[113,1210,214,1449]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 4. — A, D, G, J, Vanuatubasis bidens (Kimmins, 1958) n. comb., holotype,♂ (BMNH), anal appendages in dorsal and lateral view; B, E, H, K, V.malekulana (Kimmins,1936) n. comb.,holotype,♂ (BMNH),anal appendages in dorsal and lateral view;C, F, I, L, V.santoensis n. gen., n. sp., holotype, ♂ (SMNS: ODO 000242 K), anal appendages in dorsal and lateral views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5398651" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5398651/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); 2) inferior anal appendages significantly longer than superior appendages, forceps-like, apically curved inwards, each ending in a black tip (
<figureCitation box="[435,489,1061,1085]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[113,124,1485,1502]" captionTargetBox="[113,1209,215,1445]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[113,1210,214,1449]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 4. — A, D, G, J, Vanuatubasis bidens (Kimmins, 1958) n. comb., holotype,♂ (BMNH), anal appendages in dorsal and lateral view; B, E, H, K, V.malekulana (Kimmins,1936) n. comb.,holotype,♂ (BMNH),anal appendages in dorsal and lateral view;C, F, I, L, V.santoensis n. gen., n. sp., holotype, ♂ (SMNS: ODO 000242 K), anal appendages in dorsal and lateral views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5398651" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5398651/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); and 3) pronotal hind lobe raised and medially protruding, tapering to a rounded or acute apex (
<figureCitation box="[344,403,1114,1138]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[113,124,566,583]" captionTargetBox="[159,1202,218,524]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[113,1210,218,524]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 5. — A, Vanuatubasis malekulana (Kimmins,1936) n. comb.,paratype,♂ (BMNH),hind lobe of pronotum and mesostigmal laminae in dorsal view; B, V. santoensis n. gen., n. sp., holotype, ♂ (SMNS: ODO 000242 K), hind lobe of pronotum and mesostigmal laminae in dorsal view. Scale bar: 0.2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5398653" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5398653/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="487">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
